SCSS and `@extend` are wildly troublesome when used with classnames because they extend any instances where the target is the last piece of a selector. Now that you're using the following on line 109 of `_navs.scss`:

```
&.nav-justified {
  @extend .nav-justified;
  @extend .nav-tabs-justified;
}
```

And we use the following in our own scss:

`.nav-tabs:not(.nav-justified) { ... }`

The compiled output is:

`.nav-tabs:not(.nav-justified):not(.nav-tabs.nav-justified) { ... }`

Which is invalid CSS and breaks our styling.

When commenting out line 109 in your file, it becomes:

`.nav-tabs:not(.nav-justified)`

If you're intending to _share_ styles within your own scss, I would highly advise using a placeholder so you don't copy unwanted styles, especially since this project is intended to allow for custom compilation by users.

*Edit: Now that I review your history though, it's been this way since 2013. This is how `@extend` behaves so it's a valid complaint. I have to assume that it's only now compiling incorrectly because of a sass update.

